cs.NI, cs.LG, cs.SY, cs.MA, cs.IT 

This paper proposes a cellular network-based outdoor localization system that does not require calibration or infrastructure support. It leverages techniques borrowed from computational geometry to estimate the user's location. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. The paper also uses machine learning techniques to reduce the ambiguity area, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category. The system is designed to work in a distributed manner, which could make it relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category. The paper also discusses the mathematical techniques used to estimate the user's location, which could make it relevant to the Mathematical Aspects of Information Theory (cs.MA) category. Finally, the paper discusses the evaluation of the proposed system using real data, which could make it relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category.
